text: And I hope and pray that one day, all unborn children will be awarded the most basic of all human rights – the right to life: https://t.co/hyooxiavMg #Stand4Life https://t.co/F0jF0CB4C0
I remain committed to supporting pro-life legislation to protect the health and well-being of all women, and to save as many unborn children as we possibly can.
All of this is substantive evidence that supports Congress’ efforts to protect unborn children from the pain of an abortion procedure.
The child can suck his thumb and yawn. It can certainly feel pain.
Studies have shown that at the five-month development mark, an unborn child’s fingers, toes, eyelids, eyebrows, nails, and even eyelashes have all formed.
The Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act is reasonable legislation that would minimize the human suffering caused by abortion.

I will continue fighting to give every Texan, and every American, the ability to keep more of their hard-earned money and spend it as they wish, not as the federal government commands.
This legislation marks a significant step toward fulfilling our promise to provide the American people real, fundamental tax relief.

While I would have preferred to see the education of every child prioritized – including homeschool students – I will continue working with my colleagues in Congress to expand school choice and opportunity.
Parents can now save up to $10K per year per child to use for K-12 education expenses in public, private, and religious schools.

Texas taxpayers will now be able to write off up to $10,000 in property taxes, a measure I fought to maintain. Further, it includes my Student Opportunity Amendment, which prioritizes the education of the next generation by expanding 529 College Savings accounts.
In particular, this bill is a win for Texans.

And because we’ve significantly lowered the corporate tax rate, businesses that have fled overseas to escape our high corporate taxes will bring jobs and roughly $2.9 trillion in capital back to the American economy.

By repealing Obamacare’s individual mandate, 6.5 million Americans who have been unfairly fined by the IRS for not being able to afford health insurance will now have immediate and significant relief.

By doubling the child tax credit, and providing rate cuts for individual taxpayers in all brackets, this bill allows Americans to keep more of their hard-earned money, and brings needed relief to working families.
This tax reform bill is a huge victory for middle class families across Texas and the country https://t.co/EgOj4j25Co

text: I stand ready to work with my colleagues so we can move forward with this important debate
A true tax cut is the only way to spark economic growth, to create booming GDP, and to reduce our debt and deficit.
And we should pursue unapologetic tax cuts. If tax reform is revenue neutral, it is not a tax cut.

We should pursue the repeal of Dodd-Frank. 

We should pursue long term reforms, over a 20-30 year window, not just 5-10 years.
We should pursue a flatter, fairer rate for Americans at all income levels – ideally one low, simple, flat tax.
As we move forward, we must be bold.
So we can make it easier for families to make ends meet and small businesses to expand and create jobs.
So we can make it easier for the factory worker to pay for his child’s education
So we can make it easier for the single mom to pay her monthly mortgage
Economic growth must be our top priority...
The principles that should govern our tax reform debate are economic growth, fairness, and simplicity.
It’s one that I‘ve championed for years, and it’s essential to getting us on a path that will allow us to once and for all #AbolishTheIRS
Specifically, allowing Americans to file their taxes on a postcard is a home run proposal
To allowing for expensing of capital investments, to making reforms that will bring American jobs and companies back to the US from overseas
From lowering and flattening rates for individuals and businesses, to eliminating the death tax and the alternative minimum tax...
There are numerous positive elements in the current outline for which I have long advocated...
The priorities laid out today to reform our country’s broken, burdensome tax code are incredibly encouraging.
